  <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6 italic text-gray-300">A solo playthrough of the full campaign of <em>Goblin Commander: Unleash the Horde</em> (2003, PS2/Xbox/GameCube), played via PS2 emulation on a Steam Deck with an Xbox controller. The host is a childhood fan of the game and considers it a severely underappreciated console RTS, praising its innovative control scheme and the variety of its goblin clans. The campaign spans five acts and introduces a new enemy clan in each act.</p>

  <hr class="my-8 border-gray-700" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-cyan-300 mt-8">Core Mechanics &amp; Systems</h2>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 ml-4">
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Clan control:</strong> Each clan is bound to a face button (X, Square, etc.). Pressing the button selects that clan; units then move and attack on command. You can control units like a traditional RTS or switch to <strong class="text-cyan-400">direct/third-person control</strong> using the analog sticks.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Titans:</strong> Super units, one per clan. Must be directly controlled. Each has a unique ability — the Stone Crusher Titan can <strong class="text-cyan-400">eat enemies to restore health</strong>, making it the strongest. Hellfire and Stormbringer Titans are weaker by comparison. Only one Titan can exist at a time.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Soul Fountains:</strong> Capture points that generate souls over time (similar to resource nodes in Halo Wars 2). Position your clan next to one until it turns blue. Soul flow slows to a trickle over time but never stops.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Gold:</strong> Earned by destroying environmental objects (rocks, barrels, structures). Does <strong class="text-cyan-400">not</strong> regenerate — finite per map. Should be used for clan upgrades before turrets.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Clan Shrines:</strong> Your main production building. Trains units and unlocks upgrades. Can be destroyed by enemies. Repair cost is 25 gold (may increase per destruction).</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Upgrades:</strong> Purchasable from the Clan Shrine. Visually reflected on your units — equipment turns gold at max level. Upgrade clans fully before spending gold on turrets.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Turrets (Rock Lobbers):</strong> Placed on the map for static defense. Limited by available gold. You can only build one of each type. Cannot be built on all maps.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Drummer Unit:</strong> A special support unit that <strong class="text-cyan-400">actively heals nearby units during combat</strong>. Sound is synchronized to the drumming animation — a noted detail for a 2003 game. Considered a must-have. Appears to heal multiple clan types.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Rune Stones:</strong> Leader powers picked up from the map or purchased at the Alchemist Shop. Two can be carried at once (L2 and R2). Powers include healing, meteor strike, freeze, fog-of-war clear, earthquake, and more. Only 10 gold each at the shop.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Waypoints / Queue:</strong> Hold L1 to queue up movement waypoints. Useful for sending units on a path while you manage another clan.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Moon Gates:</strong> Teleporters. Either clan can use them regardless of color. Master Moon Gates teleport your units to linked locations on the map.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">D-pad navigation:</strong> Up returns to base; Down returns to your last position. Considered forward-thinking for a console RTS.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-cyan-400">Unit stats at mission end:</strong> Game tracks units built, units killed, and units lost per mission.</li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="my-8 border-gray-700" />

